                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d197">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">651.116 Nitrate/80: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Straus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-19T14:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 19, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 19—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. Reference Department’s telegram No. 60, February 18, 6 p.m. It is true that
                    Chile and Norway have been accorded entire nitrate quota and that United States
                    has been this morning refused participation. Embassy and Commercial Attaché in
                    particular have, however, been in almost daily communication with authorities
                    urging maintenance of our position under quota agreement of 1932.<note n="41"
                        xml:id="d197fn41">For the quota agreement of May 31, 1932, see telegram No.
                        342, May 31, 1932, from the Ambassador in France, <ref
                            target="frus1932v02#pg_232">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1932, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>,
                            p. 232</ref>.</note> Inter-ministerial meeting to decide question is
                    scheduled for tomorrow. Although we are unofficially informed that Foreign
                    Office is doing its best to support our views and nitrate buying organization is
                    favorably inclined towards purchasing small tonnage, Agriculture appears
                    in-alterably opposed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Straus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
